Arrow functions: allow us to write shorter function syntax.
Ex:
a)This demonstrates a regular function, NOT an arrow function:-
  hello = function(){
      return "hello world";
  }
  const res = hello();
  console.log(res);  //hello world

b)A demonstration of a simple arrow function.
  hello = () =>{
      return "Sandeep";
  }
  const res = hello();
  console.log(res);

c)If the function has only one statement, and the statement returns a value, you can remove the brackets and the return keyword.
  hello = () => "Sandeep"
  const res = hello();
  console.log(res);  //Note: This works only if the function has only one statement.

d)If you have parameters, you pass them inside the parentheses:
  hello = (val) => "Sandeep" + val;
  const res = hello(" LS");
  console.log(res);

e)if you have only one parameter, you can skip the parentheses as well:
  hello = val => "Sandeep" + val;
  const res = hello(" LS");
  console.log(res);
